SIMPLE: seize
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Seize
<hw>Seize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Seized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Seizing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>seisen</ets>,
<ets>saisen</ets>, OF. <ets>seisir</ets>, <ets>saisir</ets>, F.
<ets>saisir</ets>, of Teutonic origin, and akin to E. <ets>set</ets>.
The meaning is properly, to set, put, place, hence, to put in possession
of. See <er>Set</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To fall
or rush upon suddenly and lay hold of; to gripe or grasp suddenly; to
reach and grasp.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For by no means the high bank he could <qex>seize</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Seek you to <qex>seize</qex> and gripe into your hands⟦br⟧
The royalties and rights of banished Hereford?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1305 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To take possession of by force.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At last they <qex>seize</qex>⟦br⟧
The scepter, and regard not David's sons.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To invade suddenly; to take sudden hold of; to come
upon suddenly; <as>as, a fever <ex>seizes</ex> a patient</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hope and deubt alternate <qex>seize</qex> her seul.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(law)</fld> <def>To take possession of by virtue of
a warrant or other legal authority; <as>as, the sheriff <ex>seized</ex>
the debtor's goods</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To fasten; to fix.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As when a bear hath <qex>seized</qex> her cruel claws⟦br⟧
Upon the carcass of some beast too weak.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To grap with the mind; to comprehend fully and
distinctly; <as>as, to <ex>seize</ex> an idea</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To bind or fasten together with a
lashing of small stuff, as yarn or marline; <as>as, to <ex>seize</ex>
ropes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ This word, by writers on law, is commonly written
<xex>seise</xex>, in the phrase <xex>to be seised of</xex> (an estate),
as also, in composition, <xex>disseise</xex>,
<xex>disseisin</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To be seized of</b></col>, <cd>to have possession, or
right of possession; <as>as, A B was <ex>seized</ex> and possessed
<ex>of</ex> the manor of Dale.</as></cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Whom age might <xex>see
seized of</xex> what youth made prize.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Chapman.</au> --
<mcol><col><b>To seize on</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To seize
upon</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to fall on and grasp; to take hold on; to
take possession of suddenly and forcibly.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To catch; grasp; clutch; snatch; apprehend;
arrest; take; capture.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seizer</ent>⟦br⟧
